[STAGE 1 - INDUSTRIAL / FACTORY-SPECIFIC ADDENDUM]

This addendum is appended to the Stage 1 base prompt ONLY when the scene is
classified as "industrial". It overrides the base prompt where they conflict;
the base prompt still applies for zones, parent_object rules, walls, openings,
and the JSON schema.

WHY THIS ADDENDUM EXISTS
Industrial top-down scenes are not furnished rooms. The important items are
machines, material-flow equipment, storage, safety barriers, utility cabinets,
and marked circulation aisles. If you treat these as residential furniture, the
pipeline under-estimates scale and replaces factory equipment with generic
cabinets/tables.

==============================================================================
A. SCALE PRIORS FOR FACTORY SCENES
==============================================================================

A.0 OUTPUT-FIELD AXIS CONTRACT
Write `estimated_dimensions` as "W m x D m" where:
- W is the horizontal/east-west span in the image.
- D is the vertical/north-south span in the image.
The orientation must match the top-down image: if the visible floor is wider
than tall, W must be greater than D.

A.1 STANDARD INDUSTRIAL ANCHORS
Use these before guessing scale:
- Personnel door:                         W 0.9 m
- Roll-up / loading door:                 W 2.5-4.0 m
- Workbench / assembly bench:             1.5-2.4 m x 0.7-1.0 m
- CNC / machining center footprint:       2.0-3.5 m x 1.8-3.0 m
- Lathe / mill / grinder footprint:       1.5-3.0 m x 0.8-1.8 m
- Injection molding / press machine:      3.0-6.0 m x 1.5-3.0 m
- Conveyor segment visible in one room:   3.0-8.0 m x 0.6-1.2 m
- Industrial robot arm cell envelope:     3.0-5.0 m x 3.0-5.0 m
- Safety fence / machine guard height:    1.6-2.2 m
- Pallet:                                 1.2 m x 1.0 m
- Pallet rack bay:                        W 2.7 m, D 1.1 m
- Control cabinet / electrical cabinet:   W 0.8-1.2 m, D 0.4-0.8 m
- Tool cabinet:                           W 0.7-1.2 m, D 0.5-0.7 m
- Forklift / AGV lane width:              2.5-3.5 m

A.2 CLEARANCE AND CIRCULATION RULES
Industrial spaces require clearances around equipment. Do not shrink the room
to the visible machine footprints.
- Pedestrian aisle:                       >= 1.0 m
- Operator aisle in front of machines:    >= 1.2 m
- Maintenance side clearance:             >= 0.8 m
- Forklift / AGV / material aisle:        >= 2.5 m
- Robot cell fenced clearance:            robot reach + 0.8 m safety margin
- Clearance in front of electrical panels/control cabinets: >= 1.0 m
- Pallet staging lane:                    pallet depth + >= 1.2 m aisle

A.3 TYPICAL ROOM FOOTPRINTS
Treat these as guides, not exact values. Convert long/short to W/D using the
image orientation rule above.
- Small garage workshop:                         ~6 m x 5 m
- Machine-shop cell with 1-2 machines:           ~8 m x 6 m
- Robot cell with safety fence:                  ~9 m x 7 m
- Small assembly line / conveyor room:           ~12 m x 8 m
- Mixed factory floor with several workcells:    ~15 m x 10 m
- Warehouse rack aisle / pallet staging area:    ~12 m x 9 m
- Server room with 2-4 rack rows:                ~8 m x 6 m

A.4 SCALE PROCEDURE
1. Choose the clearest anchor object from A.1, preferably near image center.
2. Estimate pixels-per-metre from that anchor.
3. Measure horizontal room span (W) and vertical room span (D).
4. Cross-check against A.2 clearances and A.3 typical footprints.
5. If machines, conveyors, racks, or robot cells cannot physically fit with
   aisles, increase the estimate before returning.
6. Record evidence in `scale_reference_objects`, for example:
   "CNC assumed 2.8 m wide", "forklift aisle requires >=2.5 m",
   "robot cell safety fence implies ~9 m x 7 m".

==============================================================================
B. INDUSTRIAL OBJECT EXTRACTION RULES
==============================================================================

B.1 MAJOR FLOOR OBJECTS
The following are MAJOR floor objects, even if they are narrow or against a wall:
- Production equipment: CNC machine, lathe, milling machine, grinder, press,
  injection molding machine, laser cutter, 3D printer, compressor, pump skid.
- Material flow: conveyor, roller table, AGV, forklift, pallet, staging table.
- Robotics and safety: robot arm, robot pedestal, safety fence, machine guard,
  light curtain post, safety gate.
- Storage and utilities: pallet rack, parts rack, bin rack, tool cabinet,
  control cabinet, electrical panel, server rack, cooling unit.
- Work areas: workbench, assembly bench, inspection table, packing table.

B.2 MINOR OBJECTS
Minor objects should be visually supported and parented correctly:
- On benches/tables: tools, jigs, fixtures, parts trays, bins, workpieces,
  calipers, clipboard, tablet, small control box.
- On racks/shelves: individual bins, boxes, trays, parts containers.
- Wall-mounted: safety signs, pegboards, hose reels, cable reels, fire
  extinguishers, mounted control panels, instruction boards, clocks.
- Floor minor/small: cones, small bins, cable loops, mats, floor markers.
Do not invent residential decor such as plants, candles, throw pillows, art
prints, rugs, vases, or decorative trays unless the image clearly shows them.

B.3 OPTIONAL FIELDS FOR INDUSTRIAL OBJECTS
You MAY add these fields inside object entries. They are optional and must not
replace the required Stage 1 fields:
- `industrial_role`: one of
  "machine" | "storage" | "transport" | "safety" | "inspection" |
  "workbench" | "utility" | "server" | "other"
- `structure_hint`: one of
  "enclosed_machine" | "open_machine" | "conveyor_line" | "robot_cell" |
  "pallet_rack" | "control_cabinet" | "safety_fence" | "workbench" |
  "server_rack" | "utility_skid"
Use these hints only when the image supports them.

B.4 COMMON STRUCTURE INTERPRETATIONS
- A CNC / machining center is one enclosed machine, not a cabinet plus a desk.
- A conveyor is one long machine with belt/rollers; do not split every roller
  into separate Stage 1 objects.
- A robot cell is a robot/pedestal plus safety fence/gate/control cabinet.
  Emit the visible physical items separately when they are distinguishable.
- A pallet rack is storage infrastructure; pallets/bins sitting in it may be
  separate minor or major objects depending on size and visibility.
- Floor markings and safety lanes are architectural/floor features, not rugs.
  Put them in architectural_features if they are large markings, or minor floor
  objects if they are small movable cones/signs.

==============================================================================
C. FINAL INDUSTRIAL CHECKLIST
==============================================================================
Before returning JSON:
- Every visible machine/workcell/rack/control cabinet is in object_hierarchy.
- Clear material-flow and pedestrian aisles are reflected in scale.
- Safety fences, guard rails, and gates are not omitted.
- Control cabinets/electrical panels are not mistaken for wardrobes.
- Conveyors/assembly lines remain long and aligned with the image.
- Residential decorative defaults were not invented.
- `estimated_dimensions` uses image-horizontal W first and image-vertical D second.
